{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}} {{Infobox Jewish leader |name = Baal Shem of London |title = |image = Falckon.jpg |caption = Portrait of the Baal Shem of London by [[John Singleton Copley]]{{ref|a}} |birth_name = Hayyim Samuel Jacob Falk |birth_date = 1708 |birth_place = |death_date = 17 April 1782 (aged 73–74) |death_place = |buried = |nationality = |occupation = }} '''Hayyim Samuel Jacob Falk''' ({{lang-he-n|חיים שמואל יעקב דפאלק מרדיולה לנידו}}; Also known as the '''Baal Shem of London''' and '''Doctor Falckon'''; 1708 – 17 April 1782) was a [[rabbi]], [[Practical Kabbalah|Practical Kabbalist]] and [[alchemy|alchemist]].
==Biography== Falk was born in either [[Fürth]] in Bavaria or [[Pidhaytsi]] in [[Podolia]]. After having narrowly escaped being [[burnt at the stake]] by the authorities in [[Westphalia]] who had charged him with [[Magic (paranormal)|sorcery]], the German Count Alexander Leopold Anton von Rantzau secretly gave him refuge in Holzminden. During this stay in 1736, Falk made his impressive kabbalistic performances in Rantzau’s castle witnessed by noblemen and Alexander’s son Count Georg Ludwig Albrecht von Rantzau. In his famous ''Mémoires du comte de Rantzow'', which are referred to by many researchers as an original standard source, this young Count gives a thorough and detailed account of all these mystic demonstrations.<ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=9gZcAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA2&dq=memoires+du+comte++Rantzau+%22Je+suis+fils+d%27Alexandre%22+Mars+1714+batis%C3%A9+%C3%A0+Holczmunden&hl=de&sa=X&ei=gIeFVb_eIuW_ywP0v4HoAg&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=memoires%20du%20comte%20Grande%20%20Bretagne%20Rantzau%20%22Je%20suis%20fils%20d%27Alexandre%22%20Mars%201714%20batis%C3%A9%20%C3%A0%20Holczmunden%20George&f=false Rantzow, George Louis Albert. "Mémoires du comte de Rantzow" p. 2 and pp. 197-223, Oxford Univ.; German translation: "Die Memoiren des Grafen von Rantzau" p. 1 and pp. 70-79]</ref> Sometime after 1736, Falk arrived in London. He lived at 35 Prescott Street, London, United Kingdom and at [[Wellclose Square]], London until his death. He was a neighbour of [[Emanuel Swedenborg]] and there is some evidence that he had a significant influence on him.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodrick-Clarke|first=Nicholas|title=Review:Emanuel Swedenborg, Secret Agent on Earth and in Heaven: Jacobites, Jews, and Freemasons in Early Modern Sweden|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/reviews/review/1236}}</ref>
Rabbi [[Jacob Emden]] accused him of being a [[Sabbatean]], a supporter of [[Sabbatai Zevi]], as he invited Moses David of Podhayce, a known Sabbatean with connections to [[Jonathan Eibeschutz]], to his home.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mysticism, Magic and Kabbalah in Ashkenazi Judaism|last=Grözinger|first=Karl-Erich|author2=Dan, Joseph|year=1991|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|location=Berlin|isbn=3-11-013744-5}}</ref>
He died on 17 April 1782 and was buried in Alderney Road Cemetery, Mile End, London <ref>http://www.jewisheastend.com/sacred.html</ref> Falk bequeathed in his will an annual sum of 100 pounds to the [[Great Synagogue of London]] as well as some [[Sefer Torah]]s.
==Folklore== Many stories exist regarding Falk's extraordinary powers. According to one account, Falk made secretive visits to [[Epping Forest]] in his carriage, where he was said to have buried some treasure. On one of these occasions a wheel came loose from the vehicle on the [[Whitechapel Road]], but followed the carriage all the way to the forest. When Falk ran short of coal, he was said to have performed a magical feat involving three shirts and a ram's horn.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ceremonies, Customs, Rites, and Traditions of the Jews|last=Isaacs|first=Hyam|year=1850|publisher=William Buck|pages=355–356}}</ref> Falk was also able to keep candles burning miraculously, and to transport objects from one place to another.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}
Some claimed that he had saved the [[Great Synagogue of London|Great Synagogue]] from fire by writing something in [[Hebrew]] on the pillars of the door.
== Diary == Falk kept a diary containing records of dreams and the Kabbalistic names of angels. This can be found in the library of the [[United Synagogue]] in London. In 2002 Michal Oron published the diary and a biography of Falk.<ref>{{cite book |last= Oron|first= Michal|title= Samuel Falk, The Baal shem of London מ'בעל שד' ל'בעל שם'|publisher=[[Bialik]] Institute|year= 2002 |isbn= 965-342-850-0}}</ref> The diary is written in [[Hebrew]] and is very cryptic. The diary was published together with the diary of Falk's assistant, Tsvee Hirsch of Kalish.
